<TITLE> Business Update: Euro woes hit Asia </TITLE>
<TEXT>
 EUROPE, Feb 8 (bdnews24.com/Reuters)--- Euro zone debt concerns sent Asian shares to a five-month low, while mining shares edged up ahead of earnings and on dealmaking. Asian markets dipped to their lowest level since September on Monday, as growing concerns about the eurozone's debt problems doused regional economic optimism. The euro fell to the lowest in over 8 months, while a stronger yen hurt Japanese exporters, sending the Nikkei to a 2-month closing low. Japanese beermakers Kirin and Suntory scrapped plans to create one of the world's largest food and beverage makers with annual sales of $40 billion. Kirin, whose shares slid as much as 8 percent, said it had not been able to agree with privately-held Suntory on how to ensure management independence and transparency in the merged company. Asian mining shares edged higher ahead of earnings reports, while an unlisted Australian mining firm landed a huge deal on Sunday to export coal to China - worth $60 billion. Resourcehouse said the deal is Australia's biggest export contract in which it will supply China Power International with 30 million tonnes of coal over 20 years. The company, which has approval for a $5.6 billion loan from the Export-Import Bank of China, also wants to raise a further $3 billion in a Hong Kong IPO next mo
